    <h3>
    1. Tualatin River
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        This local river isn't a primary salmon stream, but its tributaries occasionally carry migrating Coho and Chinook—perfect for a quick, convenient outing close to Beaverton’s neighborhoods 
    </li>
    <li>
        Try near <strong>Fanno Creek</strong> or accessible banks north of downtown Beaverton when water flows permit.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    2. Willamette River
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Just east of Beaverton, the Willamette offers excellent spring and fall salmon runs
    </li>
    <li>
        Prime spots include <strong>Oregon City</strong>, the <strong>Sellwood or Sellwood–Moreland area</strong>, and stretches just downstream of the Clackamas River confluence.
    </li>
    <li>
        Techniques: back‑bouncing roe, trolling plugs like Kwikfish, or casting spinners during peak runs.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    3. Columbia River (West Portland Area)
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        About 40 minutes away, this powerhouse river features legendary spring and fall Chinook fishing 
    </li>
    <li>
        Top access points: <strong>Sauvie Island ramps</strong>, <strong>Kelley Point Park</strong>, or near the <strong>Bonneville Dam</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Best tactics include trolling herring or spinners, and drift fishing using roe under wind for bankside action.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    4. Clackamas River
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A renowned salmon water, receiving strong runs of spring and fall Chinook and Coho 
    </li>
    <li>
        Good public access at <strong>Carver Park</strong>, <strong>Milo McIver</strong>, and <strong>Eagle Creek</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Ideal gear: drift fishing with roe, spinners, or flasher‑roe combos.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    5. Sandy River
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A smaller, scenic river east of Portland; good for salmon in spring and fall 
    </li>
    <li>
        Popular spots include <strong>Glen Otto Park</strong>, <strong>Oxbow</strong>, and <strong>Dodge Park</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Fish shallow runs with roe, plugs, or small spinners amid scenic forest settings.
    </li>
</ul>
