<h2>
    Quick Tips for a Successful Trip
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Licensing</strong>: You need an <strong>Oregon angling license</strong> + <strong>Combined Angling Tag</strong> for salmon 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear advice</strong>: Use 8–10 ft medium-heavy rods, 20–30 lb test line, and leaders around 12–15 lb. Roe, plugs, and spinners are effective.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boat vs Bank</strong>: Boats expand range and access deep runs, but many spots offer productive shore fishing, especially on the Willamette and Clackamas 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Timing matters</strong>: Fish early morning and late evening—optimal bite times in warmer water.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Check conditions &amp; regs</strong>: Water clarity, flow, and hatchery versus wild fish rules change throughout the season—stay updated on ODFW site.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Final Take
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Closest &amp; easiest:</strong> Tualatin &amp; Willamette Rivers for occasional action right from the city’s edge.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best local bank fishing:</strong> Clackamas River (Carver, Eagle Creek) and Willamette at Sellwood or Oregon City.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Epic salmon runs:</strong> Columbia River via Sauvie Island, Kelley Point, or Bonneville.
    </li>
</ul>


